cence and of Experience\n|\nIf everyone started off the day singing, just think how happy they'd be.\n\n- Lauren Myracle, Shine\n|\nScience is great for us. But for someone who see the human evaluation for more than one million years, science is a just a one instant and younger than a baby.\n\n- Muditha Champika, Theories of Nature and the Universe: Comparison of Pure Buddhist Philosophy and Science\n|\nJesus said, 'Enter into My rest' and let God do what He does best\n\n- R. Alan Woods, The Journey Is The Destination: A Photo Journal\n|\nDon’t make your job your assignment. Rather, make your life assignment your career and job\n\n- Sunday\n|\nHope is a beautiful and magical thing. Grasp it tight, monsieur, and never let go.\n\n- Rachel L. Demeter, Beauty of the Beast\n|\nUpon reading, great stories by Great Spirits, the glorious inspiration penetrated our soul; we can’t help but to shed tears. It was a soul soothing and a deep spiritual awaken.\n\n- Lailah Gifty Akita, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nSounds like the start of a beautiful friendship, Leonard. It really does.” “Here’s looking at you, kid.\n\n- Matthew Quick, Forgive Me, Leonard Peacock\n|\nAlways try to live in a wonderful world where the sun is always shining, flowers are always blooming, birds are always singing, and you are always busy with a joyful life.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nNo! Try not. Do, or do not. There is no try.\n\n- George Lucas, The Star Wars Trilogy\n|\nWar is like a fire. One man may start it, but it will spread all over. It is not about one thing in particular.\n\n- T.H. White, The Once and Future King\n|\nOur objective is to achieve, by the understanding of the Origin, the Knowledge which comes through experience.\n\n- Idries Shah, Wisdom of the Idiots\n|\nObserving your thoughts, feelings & sensations is the grist of the practice.\n\n- Allan Lokos, Patience: The Art of Peaceful Living\n|\nMatched with an aged wife, I mete and doleUnequal laws unto a savage race,That hoard, and sleep, and feed, and know not me.\n\n- Alfred\n|\nOn October 14th, the sweetest thing happened to me. On that day at sunset, I met you by the sea. It was that day I found a great purpose and a wonderful reason to be.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nI had a dream about you. We couldn't decide on a sunrise. You wanted a tan, I only cared about the view. Then World War III fulfilled both our desires.\n\n- Bauvard, I Had a Dream About You\n|\n…proved that woman isn't a half but a whole human being, and can stand alone.\n\n- Louisa May Alcott, Jo's Boys\n|\nDoctrine once sown strikes deep its root, and respect for antiquity influences all men.\n\n- William\n|\nWell-being is attained little by little, and nevertheless is no little thing itself.\n\n- Zeno\n|\nI've been ignored by prettier women than you, but none who carried the heavy pitchers of silenceso far, without spilling a drop.\n\n- Jeffrey\n|\nDon't dwell too long on the past, forgive and let it go. Too many hours have been wasted on old regrets and sorrow.\n\n- Atalina Wright, Unbound\n|\nThere is still peace left in the world,and only those with beauty in their soul,care enough to be it.\n\n- Jenim Dibie, The Calligraphy of God\n|\nI imagine a line, a white line, painted on the sand and on the ocean, from me to you.\n\n- Jonathan Safran Foer, Everything Is Illuminated\n|\nYesterday I was sad, today I am happy! Yesterday I had a problem, today I still have the same problem! But today I changed the way I look at it!\n\n- C.\n|\nThis city is like no other city in the world. It is brilliant but it is bloated, and I've never called it home\n\n- Jessie Burton, The Miniaturist\n|\nWhen along the pavement,Palpitating flames of life,People flicker around me,I forget my bereavement,The gap in the great constellation,The place where a star used to be\n\n- D.H.\n|\nThey are not mad. They're trained to believe, not to know. Belief can be manipulated. Only knowledge is dangerous.\n\n- Frank Herbert, Dune Messiah\n|\nNothing disrupts dehumanization more 